SdpSerializer.js added

SdpSerializer is a library aimed to provide possible customizable
features of session description (sdp).

E.g. To set maximum audio/video/data bandwidth:

sdp = SdpSerializer.SerializeAS(sdp, {
--- audio: 100,
--- video: 300,
--- data: 10000000
});

To set "framerate" for audio streams:

sdp = SdpSerializer.SerializePTime(sdp, {
--- minptime: 2,
--- maxptime: 20
});

RTCMultiConnection-v1.4 released for early tests

It is experimental releases. Following features are excluded from this
release:

1. Streams Renegotiation
2. Auto Close Entire Session
3. Extra Data

All missing features will be added in next commits.

In this release:

1. You can us any signaling gateway for signaling; no dynamic channels
or namespaces are required. XHR POST/GET based signaling also worsk.
SIP-over-WebSockets too.

https://github.com/muaz-khan/WebRTC-Experiment/tree/master/video-conferencing#custom-signaling-channel

2. You can set "frame rate" for audio streams like this:

connection.framerate = {
--- minptime: 10,
---  maxptime: 60
};

3. You can get alerted if a stream stopped:

connection.onstreamended = function(e) {
--- document.body.removeChild(e.mediaElement);
};

4. You can stop any stream:

connection.streams['stream-id'].stop();

https://webrtc-experiment.appspot.com/RTCMultiConnection-v1.4.js

first step toward signaling simplification!

You can use each and every signaling method very easily. No dynamic
channels or namespaces required.

1. https://webrtc-experiment.appspot.com/screen-sharing/
2. https://webrtc-experiment.appspot.com/meeting/
3. https://webrtc-experiment.appspot.com/one-to-many-video-broadcasting/
4. https://webrtc-experiment.appspot.com/one-to-many-audio-broadcasting/

You need to write code like this:

meeting.openSignalingChannel = function(callback) {
return io.connect().on('message', callback);
};

and server side node.js code like this:

io.sockets.on('connection', function (socket) {
socket.on('message', function (data) {
socket.broadcast.emit('message', data);
});
});

RecordRTC supports video recording in animated GIF images

You can record audio in WAV file format; and video in either WebM format
or as animated GIF image.

https://webrtc-experiment.appspot.com/RecordRTC/

var recorder = RecordRTC({
â€” video: HTMLVideoElement
});

// start recording gif
recorder.recordGIF();

// stop recording gif
recorder.stopGIF(function(gifURL) {
â€” window.open(gifURL);
});

Fixing #38, and may be #39

Channel presence in "socket.io over node.js" can be detected like this:

function testChannelPresence(channel) {
var socket = io.connect('/');

socket.on('presence', function (isChannelPresent) {
console.log('is channel present', isChannelPresent);
if (!isChannelPresent) playRoleOfSessionInitiator();
});

socket.emit('presence', channel);
}
testChannelPresence('default-channel');

