Socket.io over Node.js source code:

https://github.com/muaz-khan/WebRTC-Experiment/tree/master/socketio-over-nodejs

Tinny fixes

It is appeared that socket.io over node.js was unable to work with
RTCMultiConnection-v1.3 because we were declaring and initializing
variables without using keyword "var".

We were setting like this:

sender = Math.round(Math.random() * 60535) + 5000;
socket = io.connect(URL + channel);

However, it must be like this:

var sender = Math.round(Math.random() * 60535) + 5000;
var socket = io.connect(URL + channel);

Link:
https://github.com/muaz-khan/WebRTC-Experiment#use-your-own-socketio-implementation

RTCMultiConnection-v1.3 is fixed for media streaming and bandwidth

Bandwidth demo:
https://webrtc-experiment.appspot.com/RTCMultiConnection/bandwidth/

Source code:

https://github.com/muaz-khan/WebRTC-Experiment/blob/master/RTCMultiConnection/RTCMultiConnection-Demos/bandwidth.html

You can set "bandwidth" like this:

connection.bandwidth = {
audio: 50,
video: 256
};

Default bandwidth for "data" m-line is 50. Customization will be
supported in next commits. E.g. you'll be able to set "bandwidth" for
data m-line like this:

connection.bandwidth = {
audio: 50,
video: 256,
data: 50
};

RTCMultiConnection-v1.3, bandwidth and direct messages

You can send direct messages like this:

connection.userid = 'muazkh';
connection.channels['muazkh'].send('hello Muaz!');

You can set bandwidth like this:

connection.bandwidth = {
audio: 50,
video: 256
}

or directly:

connection.bandwidth.audio  =50;
connection.bandwidth.video  =256;

Merging #31 and implemented #33

Custom (predefined) user-ids in DataChannel.js â€” #26 implemented

You can use custom usernames i.e. user-ids:

channel.userid = 'predefined-userid';

// or for auto-initiated data connections
new DataChannel('channel-name', {
userid: 'predefined-userid'
});

DataChannel.js is now compatible to
https://github.com/muaz-khan/WebRTC-Experiment/tree/master/socketio-over-nodejs

Have questions or issues? Submit them here:
https://github.com/muaz-khan/WebRTC-Experiment/issues/26

You can customize whether to "autoCloseEntireSession" or not!

When room initiator leaves; you can enforce auto-closing of the entire
session. By default: `autoCloseEntireSession` is `false`:

connection.autoCloseEntireSession = true;

// or
new RTCMultiConnection('session-id', {
autoCloseEntireSession: true
});

// for DataChannel.js
channel.autoCloseEntireSession = true;

// or
new DataChannel('channel-name', {
autoCloseEntireSession: true
});

**Note:** Only
[DataChannel.js](https://webrtc-experiment.appspot.com/DataChannel.js)
and
[RTCMultiConnection-v1.2.js](https://webrtc-experiment.appspot.com/RTCMultiConnection-v1.2.js)
updated.

